	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />It depends on whether you're asking about the code I write at work or the code I write for personal projects.
<br />
<br />At work I mainly use Java, and sometimes C/C++. There's practically no code optimization taking place there, because almost none of the stuff we write is speed-critical, and maintainability and stability are <strong>much</strong> more important than execution speed in our line of work.
<br />Design and maintenance usually outweigh the implementation time if you look at the entire life-span of a piece of software.
<br />
<br />When I work on my own projects it's almost the complete opposite. I barely ever design anything before writing it, and I can spend hours trying to optimize away a few bytes or cycles in a piece of code. I still fix bugs, but I tend to do very little testing.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


